narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned how to apply my knowledge to newer and more complex problems and to learn a large quantity of information in a short period of time.
I didn't gain a whole lot from this class; I was made to re-take it despite my completion of Calculus BC.
Basic skills and knowledge of calculus
I learned a great deal about single variable calculus, such as parametric and polar coordinate systems, integral calculations, and summations and series.

I learned all the necessary skills to resolve problems that are related to calculus with a single variable. I also learned how to manage my time properly and how to identify my weaknesses as well as remedy them.
integrals, areas, derivatives, parametric curves
I learned various integration techniques, how to calculate areas of parametric curves and to convert polar to Cartesian coordinates and vice versa.
Calculus.
Integration, series, area, volume of revolution
You learn the classic calc 2 topics - integrals, sequences and series, volumes, polar coordinates
Calculus

Taking this course broadened my view of math as well as of my own abilities. The pace in the course was much more aggressive then that of my high school math class, but taking this pace and seeing myself able to keep up helped me feel confident at Yale. I learned how to manage myself in order to retain material effectively as well as how to manage my time.

I developed a better skill of critical problem solving, utilizing the skills taught in class on the P-sets. While the math I've learned in the class may not be applied outside of the classroom, this method of problem solving will be.
I refreshed my knowledge on calculus II subjects such as volumes of solids of revolution and integration. I also improved my knowledge of sequences and series.

i learned more about how much work i need to do in order to really study for something. i was comfortable with the subjects in this class before entering it, but soon realized how much I wasnt actually comfortable with
I was able to solidify my prior understanding of certain calculus skills and expand on new ones.
I developed a lot of integration skills and techniques with series.
Math
I learned better study habits as well as how to work in a group to solve these problems.
Multiples applications of integrals

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The strengths are that the content was well taught but it could be improved by reducing the amount of coursework. For example, during the week that we had a math midterm, we also had the discoveries and a problem set. My suggestion would be to make the problem set for that week optional.

This course really just wasn't that engaging at all for students who already knew what they were doing, and I was pretty frustrated with the random assignments unrelated to math that we had to do on Canvas like Learning Strategy reflections.
The class was the best it could be, Professor Diethorn is the best calculus lecturer that Ive ever seen. I am so grateful for her class!

Strengths of this course include having many resources available online to access for studying and reviewing material. Weakness is that the pace of the class can be too slow or fast for some students, and it is evident in class where students fall. This makes it difficult to get through all of the material on the printed worksheets for each class because of questions.

Strengths are that Rachel is an amazing teacher that is very encouraging. The problem sets are good , the material to prep for exams sufficient. However , the explorations are not very useful in my opinion.
the class was very organized and rachel was an excellent professor
The explorations are helpful however all of the explorations should be accessible at once and not only made accessible gradually.
This course is very large and it is difficult to meaningfully engage with fellow students and professors.

I really liked how there were worksheet templates that we all filled out together in class; those really helped me not only understand the concepts when they were taught but also be able to review concepts really effectively for exams.
Strength - Lesson plans, the packets, abundance of office hours

STRENGTHS: This was a good course overall. The explorations before classes grew on me - I didn't like them at first, but I appreciated when they were shorter - it felt like less of a chore, and still was able to set the logical foundation for the next class's topic. More instructors should take note of Professor Diethorn's guided notes - it's super convenient not to have to worry about copying down the problem, so you can just focus on trying to solve it and understand. WEAKNESSES: An answer key of the problem set after it is posted - with how to work through the problems - might be helpful for reviewing for exams. Going over more complicated problems and examples in class would be helpful, including challenging questions from the problem set after it is turned in.
peer tutoring

I appreciated my professor and the great energy she brought to class everyday. It really helped motivate me at 9AM. I also appreciate the packets that we filled out together during class. Rather than taking all of the notes myself, I feel like this method allowed me to truly know what is important and made sure I never got left behind.

The strength of this course is its format. Being able to learn the content of the class, review it in the notes, and then apply it in the P-sets was very beneficial to my learning. Professor Diethorn was a key component of this and I really enjoyed learning from her. The only weakness may be the amount of assignments in Canvas, I found it difficult to follow what I needed to do and not.

The strengths of this course were that it had a decent pace and workload that taught all of the necessary material without feeling rushed. I also think the peer tutors were really helpful with p-sets and concepts. This course could be improved by maybe having additional concept review sessions throughout the semester instead of right before the midterm.
i felt it was a bit rushed while on some topics, overall it was a great class

I have no suggestions for improvement within my own course, I would rather like to say that while I had a brilliant teacher I heard lots of complaints about the other teachers who were responsible for the same course. I would suggest looking at different teachers to teach calc 115 who communicate more in the style of Rachel Diethorn
The weakness of this course may be the late peer tutoring hours and that the problem sets were at times coupled with midterms which was really challenging.
not sure yet
Strengths would be the practice tests given to us to study for the midterms. Weakness would be some of the assignments seemed to just be busy work.
It was sometimes difficult to remember things from previous units because it wasnt always reviewed until right before the exam.

I think there is disparity among sections. For example I had a really good section; my teacher gave us worksheets to follow along with the lesson and had accessible office hours. From, what I heard this wasnt true for some other ones.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, because the course was well taught and the content is important.

Not unless you have to take it. If you like math but already took Calculus BC, this will probably be an easy A but you won't learn anything and it'll be kind of a waste of time. If you're looking for a challenge take something higher up and talk to the DUS.
Yes, absolutely! The class was well structured, and assistance was readily available when needed.
Yes, especially with Rachel. She's so great and helpful
I would definitely recommend this course for learning calculus.
Yes I would !
very challenging course but rewarding
Only if it fulfills a requirement.

No. I thought the class too big and it was very hard for me to be engaged with it. My professor was wonderful but I have heard from other students that their professors were unhelpful. The large variation between classes and size of the classes detract from the course.
Yes! I felt like all the concepts were explained really well, and I loved my instructor.
Yes, but only if you need to. Its a lot of work and can be very confusing at times. Just be prepared to spend a lot of time in office hours and a lot of time reviewing the content.
This course is probably a requirement for you, but Rachel Diethorn is an amazing instructor and course coordinator - if you can take it with her, definitely do!
yes but only w/ rachel!!!!!!

I would recommend specifically Professor Diethorn's section. As previously stated, the energy really helped motivate me at 9 AM, as well as her online notes. Aside from this, I cannot judge how this course compares to most other Yale math classes as it is my first. If a student needed to take Math 115 I would not advise against it.
Yes, I found this class very beneficial to my understanding of calculus and I look forward to taking more classes in this department.
Yes, I would recommend it because it is a good foundational course for higher math classes if you need to take them for your major.
Yes, it's a prerequisite for many courses.
i would recommend taking this class, especially if its with the professor I had
Yes, I would, it was very well formatted and the information was accessible.
Yes but do the work
I would recommend this course to another student if needed for their major
Yes, the instructors were very helpful and knowledgeable.
I would, especially if you get a good section. I think the class is a pre req for many people but is definitely one that you can enjoy if you take advantage of the resources and have a good teacher.
